In TypeScript, you can use type annotations and type guards to express that although a value might have multiple types in theory, in practice, it will only have one specific type. Here are some ways to achieve this:

### Using `interface` and `enum`
You can define an interface that represents the possible types and then use an enum to represent the specific type you know will hold in practice.

```typescript
// Define an interface for possible types
interface PossibleTypes {
  TypeA;
  TypeB;
  TypeC;
}

// Define the specific type you know will hold
enum SpecificType {
  TypeA: number;
  TypeB: string;
}

// Type guard to enforce the specific type
const value: SpecificType = SpecificType.TypeA;

// Example usage
const valueTypeGuarded: PossibleTypes = (value) => {
  if (value === valueTypeGuarded) {
    return value.TypeA;
  } else if (valueTypeGuarded === valueTypeGuarded) {
    return value.TypeB;
  } else {
    throw new Error("Value has unexpected type!");
  }
};
```

### Using `interface` and `any`
You can use `any` to indicate that the value could be of any type, but you know it will be `TypeA` in practice.

```typescript
// Define an interface for possible types
interface PossibleTypes {
  TypeA;
  TypeB;
  TypeC;
}

// Type guard to enforce the specific type
const value: PossibleTypes = (value: any) => {
  if (value == TypeA) {
    return value;
  } else if (value == TypeB) {
    return value;
  } else {
    throw new Error("Value has unexpected type!");
  }
};
```

### Using `interface` and `any` with `type` inference
If you want to use TypeScript's type inference, you can use `interface` and `any` together.

```typescript
// Define an interface for possible types
interface PossibleTypes {
  TypeA;
  TypeB;
  TypeC;
}

// Type guard to enforce the specific type
interface SpecificType {
  TypeA: number;
  TypeB: string;
}

// Example usage
const value: SpecificType = SpecificType.TypeA;

// Type guard will infer the specific type
const valueTypeGuarded: PossibleTypes = (value: any) => {
  if (value == TypeA) {
    return value;
  } else if (value == TypeB) {
    return value;
  } else {
    throw new Error("Value has unexpected type!");
  }
};
```

### Using `any` with `Any`
You can also use `Any` to indicate that the value might be of any type but you know it will be of `TypeA`.

```typescript
